<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-09T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-09T08:00:00-05:00" n="1079" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1079">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72/411</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW2" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Berlin</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-09T14:00:00+01:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">August 9, 1914, 2 p.m.</hi>
                            </date>
                            <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 14, 8:30 p.m.</hi>] </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>Germany wants permission to send telegrams in cipher via Tuckerton
                            wireless station which is in connection with Eilvese station here in
                            Hanover. I suggest while waiting this permission, if you give it
                            unconditionally, for the moment, Germany allowing me to send you daily
                            one long despatch in cipher or English and that you be allowed to answer
                            it in same manner. Send <hi rend="italic">Tennessee</hi>, Rotterdam.
                            Germany wants to communicate their Embassy at Tokyo. Better keep this
                            communication your hands so we can keep this line open via
                            Tuckerton.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_GJW2">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Gerard</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>